msgid "Stability: why \"implicit\" matters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/time_integration.rst:250
#: ee8839562f464272a8e0f40497d7042e
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Forward (explicit) Euler is the simplest possible time scheme, but for "
"stiff problems — anything diffusive at meaningful mesh resolution — it "
"imposes a *CFL constraint*: the step size has to shrink with the square "
"of the mesh size, :math:`\\Delta t \\lesssim h^{2}/\\lambda_{\\max}`. "
"Backward (implicit) Euler has no such restriction. The plot below takes "
"the same heat problem on a coarse :math:`h = 0.1` mesh, adds a small "
"high-frequency perturbation to the initial condition, and runs three "
"schemes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/time_integration.rst:259
#: 6feb20ed2cc34102be5a0b22eaf15e83
msgid "Forward vs backward Euler stability on the 2D heat equation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/time_integration.rst:264
#: 2b4ba29d44554a9db771c16812a0b79e
msgid ""
"``max|u|`` over time. Forward Euler at a safe ``dt`` (green) and backward"
" Euler at a large ``dt`` (blue) both decay smoothly; forward Euler at the"
" same large ``dt`` (red) amplifies the high-frequency mode by roughly "
":math:`6 \\times` every step and blows up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/time_integration.rst:269
#: 1fa9c5d8eb164e71813ad0954f0ce6eb
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The takeaway: if the problem is stiff, pay the per-step linear solve and "
"use an implicit scheme. Forward Euler is for problems where "
":math:`\\Delta t \\le h^{2}/\\lambda_{\\max}` is *cheap enough*, which in"
" practice means hyperbolic problems (wave, transient elasticity) at their"
" natural CFL — not parabolic ones."
msgstr ""

